Mystery solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebellum prevents people from tickling themselves. This was found out by scientists at the Humboldt University in Berlin with the help of experiments on rats, as they announced on Thursday evening. In this case, progress was also made in the question of why children fight against tickling so fiercely, only to ask for more.
Finally, it was shown why the mere approach of a tickling hand triggered laughter even before the touch. This is due to a deep layer in the cerebellum that already triggers laughter when the tickling is expected.
The report said that previous research had shown that rats responded with "laughter" in the ultrasound range when tickled by humans, and that this "laughter" was mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex that was central to haptic processing.
Laughter is suppressed during self-touching
The researchers concluded that the brain could distinguish between self-touch and touch by others - and therefore humans could not tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers found in experiments on rats that laughter and the activity of the corresponding area of the cerebral cortex were suppressed during self-touch. This was also true when living things cleaned themselves. During the time of self-touch and tickling, the scientists had enhanced the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh.
But if self-touch and other people's touch occur at the same time, laughter is suppressed, too, which suggests that the rat brain simply cannot distinguish between self-touch and other people's touch, and the new findings suggest that humans cannot tickle themselves because self-touch activates a brake in the cerebellum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves, but in the experiment they sometimes broke off this initiation prematurely, showing flight or stubborn fear, an ambivalence similar to that of children, and the ambivalence of tickling is a behavioral response similar to that of rats and humans.
