Attention: Smartphone NEVER be charged without a cable
Practical but Harmful
Inductive technique via Qi standard is extremely practical, but should not be used.
With the recent launch of several new smartphones that support wireless charging and sell very well - the new iPhone 11 models in particular - we would like to recall a study from the beginning of July.
Higher temperature is killing the battery.
Researchers warn against wireless charging of smartphones. This is extremely harmful to the devices according to the findings of the Univerity of Warwick. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat development. If you charge a mobile phone normally by cable, the battery heats up within three hours to 27 degrees. With wireless charging, the researchers have always measured over 30 degrees even with perfect orientation of the smartphone on the charging pad. If the mobile phone is located next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the wattage of the charging pad also increases, which in turn drives up the power consumption.
Capacity and service life
The researchers say that the temperature is a decisive factor in the battery's durability. Each degree plays a role. When charging at higher temperatures, the battery not only loses capacity, but it also lasts less overall. The lifespan is therefore shorter. The researchers therefore advise to always charge the smartphone by cable. Since a battery change in modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, this may be a helpful tip. According to Apple, the cost of a battery change has recently increased even once again - and that is for all iPhones.
Practical
The technology is extremely convenient: Simply place the device on a suitable charging pad - these are now installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without the hassle of cable wiring and a tedious plug finger. Since Qi (stands for inductive energy transfer) is a worldwide standard, which, exceptionally, even Apple is involved, there are few restrictions.
