Comet from another star crosses solar system
Astronomers are observing a comet from deep in space, and it's the first time they've done that, and it's leading to clues about other solar systems.
What was once just a guess has now been confirmed: an interstellar guest is passing through our solar system, the comet from deep space has been named 2I/Borisov after its discoverer and has sparked the interest of astronomers around the world.
The most distant comet was discovered on August 30 by amateur astronomer Gennady Borisov at the Margo Observatory in Crimea - with a self-built telescope of 65 centimeters in diameter. Observations by various observatories not only confirmed that it was an unknown comet, but also showed that it did not come from our solar system.
2I/Borisov is only the second interstellar object to be observed during a transit of our solar system, after 1I/'Oumuamua in 2017.
2I/Borisov offers astronomers a rare chance to get close-up views of an alien solar system before it disappears forever. Early observations show that the interstellar comet resembles those in our own solar system, as reported by the Canary Islands Astrophysical Institute. "The current speed of the comet is high, about 150,000 kilometres per hour, which is well above the typical speeds of objects orbiting the sun at this distance", said Davide Farnocchia of the US space agency NASA in a statement.
The comet is in a hyperbolic orbit, which leads it out of our system, and is clearly of interstellar origin, as reported by the International Astronomical Union (IAU). It is also responsible for the naming and categorization of celestial bodies. In honor of its discoverer, the interstellar comet, which was initially listed under the catalog number C/2019 Q4, was designated 2I/Borisov, with the first part of the name indicating that it is the second interstellar object discovered in our solar system.
Astronomers are lucky: Unlike 1I/'Oumuamua, 2I/Borisov was observed on approach, giving researchers many months to study it. "The object will reach its maximum brightness in mid-December and will be visible with medium-sized telescopes until April 2020", explained Farnocchia. "After that, it will only be visible with larger, professional telescopes until October 2020".
The comet was first observed by the Gemini Observatory in Hawaii, which determined that the comet was between 2 and 16 kilometers in diameter, and that the comet was moving in a direction that was not previously known.
Researchers from the Instituto de Astrof√≠sica de Canarias (IAC) have already obtained the first spectrum from the interstellar tail star, which provides a fingerprint of its chemical composition. "The spectrum of this object is similar to that of comets in our solar system, and this indicates that its composition must be similar", reported IAC researcher Julia de Lic√≥n.
