If the provider promises too much performance
If the Internet connection always seems to be much slower than advertised by the provider, there are several ways of checking.
The Internet contract does not require you to rely blindly on the speed data provided by the provider, but rather to check for yourself how much is actually achieved.
The Commission has therefore decided to initiate the procedure laid down in Article 108 (2) of the Treaty in respect of the application of the principle of proportionality.
If the connection always seems to be much slower than advertised by the provider, there are several ways of checking this: the measuring tools of the Federal Network Agency (BNetzA) measure the actual data transmission rates and compare them with the rate agreed in the contract.
'The tests of the providers are however carried out according to the specifications of the providers and are therefore not uniform and objectively calculated,' the consumer centre Bavaria points out.
If the connection is much slower than advertised, customers can give the provider a reasonable period of time, usually 14 days, to deliver the promised service.
If this does not work after repeated requests, customers can terminate and possibly also claim damages.
